Luca's response on the jsp stuff:


Hi Sylvia,
we actually don't have a single JSP page that I can send you to subscribe people - the subscription process is part of a much
more involved workflow that involves both JSP pages \(the "view"\), Spring controllers \(the "control"\) and service Java classes \(the "model"\). It goes pretty much like this:

o there's a JSP page where a user inserts an email \(among other things\). The JSP page gets submitted to a controller:

&lt;form action="subscribeToList.htm"&gt;
Enter your email: &lt;input type="text" name="email" size="20"&gt;&lt;/input&gt;
&lt;input type="submit" value="subscribe me"/&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;

o The controller parses the HTTP request and invokes the Java service class:

public classs SubscribeController extends AbstractCommandController \{


public void handle\(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response\) \{

String from = request.getParameter\("email"\);
String to = "esmf-join@ucar.edu";
String subject = "subscription";
String content = "none";
Email.send\(from, to, subject, content\);	

\}

\}

o The Java service class sends the email, I include the full listing at the end.

All of this machinery needs to run within a Tomcat servlet container... as you can see, it's not something you can setup in 5 minutes. If you guys are in a hurry for setting something up,
maybe your best bet is to write a perl script that is invoked via a form subscription. Otherwise, if you want to go the Java way and need some help, please come see me after Thanksgivingg, I'll
be happy to give you more pointers.

thanks, Luca

